Define period length \(\Delta t\)Population change \(N(t + \Delta t) - N(t) = \Delta N(t)\)11Person-years lived now \(N(t)\Delta t\)12So crude growth rate now \(r(t) = \frac{\Delta N(t)}{N(t) \Delta t}\)KEY CONCEPTInstantaneous growth rate = crude growth rate tiny period \(\Delta t\)Mathematically13:\[\begin{equation}
  r(t) = \lim_{\Delta t \0} \frac{d \text{ln}\left[N(t)\right]}{dt}
  \tag{1.1}
\end{equation}\]can algebra using Equation (1.1) express instantaneous growth accumulates times \(0\) \(T\)14:\[\frac{N(T)}{N(0)} = e^{\int_0^T r(t)dt}\]Left-hand side: Ratio ending starting population sizeRight-hand side: Expression accumulated growthRe-arranging:\[\begin{equation}
  N(T) = N(0)e^{\int_0^T r(t)dt}
  \tag{1.2}
\end{equation}\]Assuming constant growth rate \(r^*\)15:\[\begin{equation}
  N(T) = N(0)e^{r^{*} T}
  \tag{1.3}
\end{equation}\]can use Equation (1.3) come estimate growth rate using just population counts period duration:\[\begin{equation}
  r^{*} = \frac{\text{ln} \left[\frac{N(T)}{N(0)}\right]}{T}
  \tag{1.4}
\end{equation}\]

exponentiate sides (1.2) divided \(T\), get:\[
  \frac{\int_0^T r(t)dt}{T} = \frac{\text{ln} \left[\frac{N(T)}{N(0)}\right]}{T}
\]
left-hand side just mean growth rate \(\bar{r}[0,T]\), :\[
  \bar{r}[0,T] = \frac{\text{ln} \left[\frac{N(T)}{N(0)}\right]}{T}
\]left-hand side known mean annualized growth rate

pgs 13-14, PHG show assume constant growth rate, can estimate person years using starting ending population counts:\[\begin{equation}
    PY[0,T] = \frac{N(T) - N(0)}{r[0,T]}
            = \frac{N(T) - N(0)}{\text{ln}\left[\frac{N(T)}{N(0)}\right]}
  \tag{1.5}
\end{equation}\]

