Consider crude death rate \(CDR[0,T] = D/N\) measured death counts \(D\) mid-period population size19 \(N\):\[
\begin{align}
CDR &= \frac{D}{N}
     = \frac{\sum_{x=0}^{\infty} {}_{n}D_{x}}{N}
     = \frac{\sum_{x=0}^{\infty} \frac{{}_{n}D_{x}}{{}_{n}N_{x}}{}_{n}N_{x}}{N} \\
    &= \sum_{x=0}^{\infty} \frac{{}_{n}D_{x}}{{}_{n}N_{x}} \cdot \frac{{}_{n}N_{x}}{N} \\
    &= \sum_{x=0}^{\infty} {}_{n}M_{x}\cdot {}_{n}C_{x} \\
    &= \textsf{Sum age groups }
       \begin{pmatrix}
        \textsf{Age-specific} \\
        \textsf{mortality rate}
       \end{pmatrix}
       \times \begin{pmatrix}
        \textsf{Proportion } \\
        \textsf{age group}
       \end{pmatrix}
\end{align}
\]Points keep mind equation:\({}_{n}C_{x} = {}_{n}N_{x} / N\) proportion population aged \(x\) \(x+n\)\(C_i\) can also interpreted proportion person-years lived aged \(x\) \(x+n\)\(\sum_{x=0}^\infty {}_{n}C_{x} = 1\)set \(C_i\) defines population‚Äôs age structureIn practice, sum oldest age group populationWith age intervals inequal length, can index age groups \(\):\[CDR = \sum_{}^{\infty} M_{}\cdot C_{}\]result can resolve confusing cross-spatial cross-temporal comparisons.EXAMPLEBelow crude death rates U.S. women 1933 vs.¬†201920. CDR higher 1933. Makes sense. 1933 height Great Depression. ‚Äôd expect bigger gap. WTF?Population older 2019Mortality higher older agesThis explain things

demographer data scientist, ‚Äôll get questions lot:Demography: ‚Äúmuch difference death rates due differences age distributions?‚ÄùPeople analytics: ‚Äúmuch difference turnover rates due different tenure distributions?‚ÄùMarketing: ‚Äúmuch customer conversion rate two lead generating websites due difference marketing channel?‚ÄùOne way answer questions clever difference decomposition.Example: Crude death rate difference\[
\Delta = CDR^B - CDR^= \sum_i C_i^B \cdot M_i^B - \sum_i C_i^\cdot M_i^
\]
pg. 28, PHG derive useful decomposition difference:\[
\begin{align}
\Delta &= \sum_i \left(C_i^B-C_i^\right) \cdot \left[\frac{M_i^B-M_i^}{2}\right] + \sum_i \left(M_i^B-M_i^\right) \cdot \left[\frac{C_i^B+C_i^}{2}\right] \\
       &= \begin{pmatrix}
        \textsf{difference age} \\
        \textsf{composition}
       \end{pmatrix}
       \cdot \begin{pmatrix}
        \textsf{weighted avg} \\
        \textsf{age-specific mortality}
       \end{pmatrix} \\
      &+ \begin{pmatrix}
        \textsf{difference } \\
        \text{rate schedules}
       \end{pmatrix}
       \cdot \begin{pmatrix}
        \textsf{weighted } \\
        \textsf{average age} \\
        \textsf{composition}
       \end{pmatrix}
\end{align}
\], put even simply:\[
\Delta = \begin{pmatrix}
  \textsf{contribution } \\
    \textsf{age composition} \\
    \textsf{differences } \Delta
  \end{pmatrix}
  + \begin{pmatrix} \\
    \textsf{contribution } \\
    \textsf{rate schedule} \\
    \textsf{differences } \Delta
  \end{pmatrix}
\]Example: Decomposing difference U.S. women‚Äôs mortality 1933 vs.¬†2019. table period age-specific population proportions \(C_i^\textsf{year}\) mortality rates \(M_i^\textsf{year}\), well difference contributions \(\left(C_i^{1933}-C_i^{2019}\right) \cdot \left(M_i^{1933}-M_i^{2019}\right)/2\) \(\left(M_i^{1933}-M_i^{2019}\right) \cdot \left(C_i^{1933}-C_i^{2019}\right)/2\).Age structure contribution negative 1933 population youngerRate schedule contribution positive 1933 mortality higherThe sum two contributions yields back original difference:\[
\Delta = CDR^{1933} - CDR^{2019} = 1.4 \textsf{ per 1000 women}
\]

